 about 800 bucks to spend on a new computer!  If anyone has any ideas on where to get a decent one at that price, a link would be much appreciated.  Otherwise, I know how to build my own, but I'm not really up to date on the newest brands and crap (I built this Athalon 750 about 2 years ago).  So if anyone REALLY wants to help me out, if you could jot down a list of good stuff (brand names, speeds, etc) and approx price that would be super.  I already have an ethernet card, but I want new everything else pretty much... thanks!!! <p><BR><BR><CENTER><IMG SRC="http://www.myezboard.com/projects/ezboard/ezboard_userimages/midnightfury/images/kyatarisig.jpg"></CENTER><BR><FONT FACE="Arial, Heveltica"><H6>I guess it's no use, screwing up every little thing I ever try to do.  I'm born to lose... yeah.  God must hate me, cursed me for eternity.  God must hate me, maybe you should pray for me.  I'm breaking down and you can't save me, stuck in hell and I wanna go home.  What in the world am I supposed to do?  I never did anything to you, so can't you find something else to do?<P>  <CENTER>Simple Plan</CENTER></FONT></H6></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/utovectris.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tovectris</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 50<br> <font color=#E9D756>(7/28/02 8:44:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=10230.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> $800 for a computer...</span><hr size=1> I wouldn't touch AMD right now for anything. They're going to crap real fast. That said, I'd go with this setup...<br>
<br>
Gigabyte 8IEXP mobo - I've run about 10 of these out in several configs as of late, and I must say that these are the most unbelievable boards I've ever worked with. Gigabyte has never really been known for having the best gear, but they've totally redeemed their name with this one board.<br>
<br>
Intel Processor - I know, they're more expensive. You'll get more performance and better speeds out of a cheaper AMD processor, but you'll also pick up a 50% chance of having a useless machine with terrible USB support, unsynced PCI, and about 50db of noise if you go with an AMD over Intel. Pay more, run quieter, and enjoy life with Intel. The 2.0Ghz Northwood seems to be a good buy these days.<br>
<br>
Hard drives are anybody's guess. I'd suggest nothing under 7200rpm and nothing by Western Digital. Then again, I've just had bad luck with them.<br>
<br>
Pick up a half gig or more of DDR RAM.<br>
<br>
Video cards are weird these days. GeForce MX cards are total and utter @#%$ (don't bother flaming me unless you've tried an MX next to a 4600). The GeForce3 is still an awesome card as long as you go with a titanium 500 or even 200. The GeForce4 is a hot board, but carries a hot price.<br>
<br>
The SB Audigy is a sweet board at only $65. It's a must have, in my opinion.<br>
<br>
Throw in a floppy drive, a few round cables, a mid-tower case, an aftermarket heatsink/fan, and anything else...I'm guessing you'll have a larger price tag than $800, but not by much. Damn.<br>
<br>
Try Googlegear for reasonable prices. (<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.googlegear.com)">www.googlegear.com)</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
If not them, check out Essential Computers (<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.essencompu.com/)">www.essencompu.com/)</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
When you're all done, ignore everything I've said and keep shopping. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uigota.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Igota</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 1001<br> <font color=#E9D756>(7/28/02 11:15:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=10230.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: $800 for a computer...</span><hr size=1> Well, I have to dissagree.<br>
<br>
Get a good 80mm heatsink and a nice quiet 80mm fan for it and your AMD will not be any louder then the HDD's or cd-rom. I have no idea what you mean by 50% chance of failure, the PCI sync, and the USB support is not perfect no but with the right motherboard it is for all practical purposes.<br>
<br>
That said, here is what I would do.<br>
<br>
Abit KR7-A =$80.<br>
Athlon XP 1800+, $100.<br>
512MB Crucial PC2100 DDR, about $130.<br>
Alpha PAL8045 heatsink and an 80mm fan, about $40.<br>
GeForce4 Ti4200, about $150-$170.<br>
60-80GB 7200rpm ata100 HDD, around $100.<br>
SoundBlaster Audigy, $65.<br>
Case: Enermax, <a href='http://www.newegg.com/app/Showimage.asp?image=11-124-026-01.JPG/11-124-026-02.JPG/11-124-026-03.JPG/11-124-026-04.JPG/11-124-026-05.JPG/11-124-026-06.JPG/11-124-026-07.JPG/11-124-026-08.JPG/11-124-026-09.JPG'>FS-501B</a>, about $60.<br>
Floppy Drive, $10<br>
Cables will come with your abit motherboard.<br>
<a href='http://www.newegg.com/app/Showimage.asp?image=23-109-106-01.JPG/23-109-106-02.JPG/23-109-106-03.JPG'>Keyboard and Mouse</a>, $25.<br>
CD-ROM, $35.<br>
<br>
You are looking at just over 800, a new netcard is aobut $15 and you could keep your old computer and have one to surf the net on while you play :)<br>
<br>
A couple things to think on.<br>
<br>
No mattter if you go with Intel or AMD, make sure your case has at least a 300 watt power supply, I chose the enermax one because they make awesome powersupplies and it looks good as well.<br>
<br>
That heat sink can only be mounted on some motherboards, not all, the MB I reccomended is one that is compatable. It is a bit tricky to install, but they have a webpage taht gives you step by step directions with pictures.<br>
<br>
You can get a 512MB stick of that ram for about 100, but I feel that RAM is one of those things that you do not skimp on, Crucial is a very good company and it is not that much more cash.<br>
<br>
If you do get that case, the B in the name is for Black, the same case is available in white (FS-501W). If you do get the black one make sure your floppy drive and cd-rom are black, otherwise it will look really bad.<br>
<br>
On the hard drive front, I would get a IBM 120GXP 80GB, but that is just me, I really like the IBM drives, as long as it is not from the 75GXP series.<br>
<br>
<br>
A great place to check for prices is <a href='http://www.pricewatch.com'>PriceWatch</a>. And another good place to buy (and where I do all my computer shopping) is <a href='http://www.newegg.com'>NewEgg</a>. They have fantastic customer service and very good prices.<br>
